Definition 1.2.1. Given any dependent type theory $\mathbf{T}$, the syntactic category $\mathcal{C}({\mathbf{T}})$ is given as follows: • objects of $\mathcal{C}({\mathbf{T}})$ are contexts $[x_{1}\mathord{:}A_{1},\ \ldots,\ x_{n}\mathord{:}A_{n}]$ of $\mathbf{T}$, up to definitional equality and renaming of free variables; • maps of $\mathcal{C}({\mathbf{T}})$ are context morphisms (a.k.a. substitutions), again up to definitional equality and renaming of free variables. That is, a map $f\colon[x_{1}\mathord{:}A_{1},\ \ldots,\ x_{n}\mathord{:}A_{n}]\>\hbox{\raise 0% .0pt\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749% 943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt% \raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt% \hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.% 0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt% \hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057% pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont\char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0% .0pt\raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114% pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox{\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt % depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces}}}\>[y_{1}\mathord{:}B_{1},\ \ldots,\ % y_{m}\mathord{:}B_{m}(y_{1},\ldots,y_{m-1})]$ is represented by a sequence of terms $\begin{split}\displaystyle x_{1}\mathord{:}A_{1},\ \ldots,\ x_{n}\mathord{:}A_% {n}&\displaystyle\vdash f_{1}:B_{1}\\ &\displaystyle\vdots\\ \displaystyle x_{1}\mathord{:}A_{1},\ \ldots,\ x_{n}\mathord{:}A_{n}&% \displaystyle\vdash f_{m}:B_{m}(f_{1},\ \ldots,\ f_{m-1}).\end{split}$ Moreover, $\mathcal{C}({\mathbf{T}})$ may naturally be given the structure of a contextual category; for each logical rule of $\mathbf{T}$, $\mathcal{C}({\mathbf{T}})$ carries the corresponding algebraic structure.
Definition 2.7. Given any pair $[\delta]$, $[\eta]$ as before, we define their vertical composition as: $[\eta]\ast[\delta]:=[\gamma]:[\hat{g}^{1}]\circ[\hat{f}^{1}]\Longrightarrow[% \hat{g}^{2}]\circ[\hat{f}^{2}].$
Definition 4.7. We define the $2$-categories $(\mathbf{\acute{E}\,Gpd})$, $(\mathbf{P\acute{E}\,Gpd})$ and $(\mathbf{PE\acute{E}\,Gpd})$ as full $2$-subcategories of $(\mathbf{Lie\,Gpd})$ by restricting to étale Lie groupoids, respectively proper étale Lie groupoids, respectively proper, effective, étale Lie groupoids. Morphisms and $2$-morphisms are simply restricted according to that. The aim of this section is to describe a $2$-functor $F$ from $(\mathbf{Red\,Atl})$ to $(\mathbf{PE\acute{E}\,Gpd})$.
Definition 1.7. [MP, §1] Let $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{U}^{\prime}$ be reduced orbifold atlases for the same topological space $X$. We say that they are equivalent if their union is again an orbifold atlas for $X$, i.e. if and only if any chart of $\mathcal{U}$ is compatible with any chart of $\mathcal{U}^{\prime}$. This gives a partial order on the set of atlases for $X$; a reduced orbifold structure of dimension $n$ on $X$ is any maximal orbifold atlas in that set, or equivalently, any equivalence class with respect to compatibility of atlases. A reduced orbifold of dimension $n$ is any pair $(X,[\mathcal{U}])$ consisting of a paracompact, second countable, Hausdorff topological space $X$ and a reduced orbifold structure $[\mathcal{U}]$ on $X$. Any atlas in $[\mathcal{U}]$ is called an orbifold atlas for $(X,[\mathcal{U}])$.
Definition 1.13. Let us fix any orbifold atlas $\mathcal{U}:=\{(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ on a topological space $X$ and let $\mathcal{U}^{\textrm{max}}$ be the maximal atlas associated to $\mathcal{U}$. Then there is an obvious morphism $\iota_{\mathcal{U}}$ over $\textrm{id}_{X}$ from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{U}^{\textrm{max}}$ given by considering every chart in $\mathcal{U}$ as a chart in $\mathcal{U}^{\textrm{max}}$ and by considering every change of charts in $\mathcal{U}$ as a change of charts in $\mathcal{U}^{\textrm{max}}$ (in particular, we can choose as good subset $P$ the set $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U})\subseteq\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U}^{\textrm{max}})$).
Definition 4.2. [M, §2.1] Given two Lie groupoids $R\rightrightarrows^{\hskip-7.113189pt{}^{s}}_{\hskip-7.113189pt{}_{t}}U$ and $R^{\prime}\rightrightarrows^{\hskip-7.966772pt{}^{s^{\prime}}}_{\hskip-7.96677% 2pt{}_{t^{\prime}}}U^{\prime}$, a morphism between them is any pair $(\psi,\Psi)$, where $\psi:U\rightarrow U^{\prime}$ and $\Psi:R\rightarrow R^{\prime}$ are smooth morphisms, which together commute with all structure morphisms of the two Lie groupoid. In other words, we ask that $s^{\prime}\circ\Psi=\psi\circ s$, $t^{\prime}\circ\Psi=\psi\circ t$, $\Psi\circ e=e^{\prime}\circ\psi$, $\Psi\circ m=m^{\prime}\circ(\Psi\times\Psi)$ and $\Psi\circ i=i^{\prime}\circ\Psi$.
Definition 8.4. Given any pair of morphisms of reduced orbifold atlases $[\hat{f}^{m}]:\mathcal{U}^{m}\rightarrow\mathcal{V}^{m}$ for $m=1,2$, we say that $[\hat{f}^{1}]$ is equivalent to $[\hat{f}^{2}]$ if and only if the following conditions hold: (a) $\mathcal{V}^{1}$ and $\mathcal{V}^{2}$ are equivalent orbifold atlases (see definition 1.7); we denote by $\mathcal{V}^{\textrm{max}}$ the maximal atlas associated to both and by $\iota_{\mathcal{V}^{m}}$ the “inclusion” of $\mathcal{V}^{m}$ in $\mathcal{V}^{\textrm{max}}$ for $m=1,2$ (see definition 1.13); (b) there exists an atlas $\mathcal{U}$, a pair of unit weak equivalences $[\hat{w}^{1}],[\hat{w}^{2}]$ and a $2$-morphism $[\delta]$ as in the following diagram: $\mathcal{U}^{1}$$\mathcal{V}^{1}$$\mathcal{U}$$\Downarrow\,[\delta]$$\mathcal{V}^{\textrm{max}}.$$\mathcal{U}^{2}$$\mathcal{V}^{2}$$\scriptstyle{\iota_{\mathcal{V}^{1}}}$$\scriptstyle{[\hat{f}^{2}]}$$\scriptstyle{[\hat{w}^{2}]}$$\scriptstyle{[\hat{w}^{1}]}$$\scriptstyle{\iota_{\mathcal{V}^{2}}}$$\scriptstyle{[\hat{f}^{1}]}$ In particular, by lemma 8.2 we have $[\mathcal{U}^{1}]=[\mathcal{U}^{2}]$; moreover $[\mathcal{V}^{1}]=[\mathcal{V}^{2}]$. The previous relation is clearly symmetric and reflexive (by lemma 3.2). Also transitivity is straightforward by using (U2) and (U3), [PS, lemma 8.1] and the construction performed in the proof of lemma 8.2. We denote by $[[\hat{f}^{1}]]=[[\hat{f}^{2}]]$ the class of any morphism as before and we say that it is a morphism from $[\mathcal{U}^{1}]=[\mathcal{U}^{2}]$ to $[\mathcal{V}^{1}]=[\mathcal{V}^{2}]$.
Definition 1.19. Let us fix any continuous function $f:X\rightarrow Y$ and let $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ be orbifold atlases for $X$ and $Y$ respectively. Moreover, let us fix $2$ morphisms $[\hat{f}^{1}]$, $[\hat{f}^{2}]$ from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{V}$ over $f$ and let us fix 2 representatives of $2$-morphisms from $[\hat{f}^{1}]$ to $[\hat{f}^{2}]$: $\delta:=\left\{\left(\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a},\delta_{i}^{a}\right)\right\}_{i\in I% ,a\in A(i)},\quad\overline{\delta}:=\left\{\left(\widetilde{U}_{i}^{\overline{% a}},\overline{\delta}_{i}^{\overline{a}}\right)\right\}_{i\in I,\overline{a}% \in\overline{A}(i)}.$ Then we say that $\delta$ is equivalent to $\overline{\delta}$ if and only if for all $i\in I$, for all pairs $(a,\overline{a})\in A(i)\times\overline{A}(i)$ and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}\cap\widetilde{U}_{i}^{\overline{a}}$ (if non-empty) we have $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\delta_{i}^{a}=% \operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\overline{\delta% }_{i}^{\overline{a}}.$ This definition gives rise to an equivalence relation (it is reflexive by (R4)). We denote by $[\delta]:[\hat{f}^{1}]\Rightarrow[\hat{f}^{2}]$ the class of any $\delta$ as before and we say that $[\delta]$ is a $2$-morphism from $[\hat{f}^{1}]$ to $[\hat{f}^{2}]$.
Definition 4.5. [M, §1.2 and 1.5] A Lie groupoid $R\rightrightarrows^{\hskip-7.113189pt{}^{s}}_{\hskip-7.113189pt{}_{t}}U$ is proper if the map $(s,t):R\rightarrow U\times U$ is proper; it is étale if the maps $s$ and $t$ are both étale (i.e. local diffeomorphisms).
Definition 1.11. Let $\mathcal{U}=\{(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ and $\mathcal{V}=\{(\widetilde{V}_{j},H_{j},\phi_{j})\}_{j\in J}$ be orbifold atlases for $X$ and $Y$ respectively. Then a representative of a morphism from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{V}$ is any tuple $\hat{f}:=(f,\overline{f},\{\widetilde{f}_{i}\}_{i\in I},P_{f},\nu_{f})$ that satisfies the following conditions: (Q1) $f:X\rightarrow Y$ is any continuous map; (Q2) $\overline{f}:I\rightarrow J$ is any set map; (Q3) for each $i\in I$, the map $\widetilde{f}_{i}$ is a local lift of $f$ with respect to the orbifold charts$(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\in\mathcal{U}$ and $(\widetilde{V}_{\overline{f}(i)},H_{\overline{f}(i)},\phi_{\overline{f}(i)})% \in\mathcal{V}$; (Q4) $P$ is any good subset of $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U})$; (Q5) $\nu_{f}:P\rightarrow\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{V})$ is any set map that assigns to each $\lambda\in P(i,i^{\prime})$ a change of charts $\nu_{f}(\lambda)\in\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{V},\overline{f}(i),\overline{f}(i^{% \prime}))$, such that: (a) $\operatorname{dom}\nu_{f}(\lambda)$ is an open set containing $\widetilde{f}_{i}(\operatorname{dom}\lambda)$, (b) $\operatorname{cod}\nu_{f}(\lambda)$ is an open set containing $\widetilde{f}_{i^{\prime}}(\operatorname{cod}\lambda)$, (c) $\widetilde{f}_{i^{\prime}}\circ\lambda=\nu_{f}(\lambda)\circ{\widetilde{f}_{i}% }|_{\operatorname{dom}\lambda}$, (d) for all $i\in I$, for all $\lambda,\lambda^{\prime}\in P_{f}(i,-)$ and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\operatorname{dom}\lambda\cap\operatorname{dom}\lambda^{\prime}$ with $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}_{i}}\lambda=\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde% {x}_{i}}\lambda^{\prime}$, we have $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu_{f}(\lambda)=% \operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu_{f}(\lambda^{% \prime}),$ (e) for all $(i,i^{\prime},i^{\prime\prime})\in I^{3}$, for all $\lambda\in P_{f}(i,i^{\prime})$, for all $\mu\in P_{f}(i^{\prime},i^{\prime\prime})$ and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\lambda^{-1}(\operatorname{cod}\lambda\cap\operatorname{% dom}\mu)$ we have $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i^{\prime}}(\lambda(\widetilde{x}_{i}))}% \nu_{f}(\mu)\cdot\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu% _{f}(\lambda)=\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu_{f% }(\eta)$ where $\eta$ is any element of $P(i,i^{\prime\prime})$ such that $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}_{i}}\eta=\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}% _{i}}\mu\circ\lambda$ (it exists by (P1)), (f) for all $i\in I$, for all $\lambda\in P(i,i)$ and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\operatorname{dom}\lambda$ such that $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}_{i}}\lambda=\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde% {x}_{i}}\textrm{id}_{\widetilde{U}_{i}}$, we have $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu_{f}(\lambda)=% \operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\textrm{id}_{% \widetilde{V}_{\overline{f}(i)}}.$
Definition 5.1. [Pr, conditions 2.1] Given any $2$-category or bicategory $\mathbf{\mathscr{C}}$, a subset $\mathbf{W}$ of $1$-morphisms of $\mathbf{\mathscr{C}}$ is said to admit a right calculus of fractions if it satisfies the following conditions (U1) all equivalences are in $\mathbf{W}$; (U2) $\mathbf{W}$ is closed under compositions; (U3) for every morphism $w:A\rightarrow B$ in $\mathbf{W}$ and every morphism $f:C\rightarrow B$, there exist a pair of morphisms $v:D\rightarrow C$ in $\mathbf{W}$ and $g:D\rightarrow A$ and an invertible $2$-morphism $\alpha:w\circ g\Rightarrow f\circ v$; (U4) (i) given any morphism $w:B\rightarrow A$ in $\mathbf{W}$, any pair of morphisms $f,g:C\rightarrow B$ and any $\alpha:w\circ f\Rightarrow w\circ g$, there exists a morphism $v:D\rightarrow C$ in $\mathbf{W}$ and a $2$-morphism $\beta:f\circ v\Rightarrow g\circ v$ such that $\alpha\ast i_{v}=i_{w}\ast\beta$; (ii) if $\alpha$ as in (i) is invertible, then so is $\beta$; (iii) if $(v^{\prime}:D^{\prime}\rightarrow C,\beta^{\prime}:f\circ v^{\prime}% \Rightarrow g\circ v^{\prime})$ is another pair with the same properties of $(v,\beta)$ in (i), then there exist $2$ morphisms $u:E\rightarrow D$, $u^{\prime}:E\rightarrow D^{\prime}$ and an invertible $2$-morphism $\varepsilon:v\circ u\Rightarrow v^{\prime}\circ u^{\prime}$ such that $v\circ u$ and $v^{\prime}\circ u^{\prime}$ are both in $\mathbf{W}$ and $\Big{(}i_{g}\ast\varepsilon\Big{)}\odot\Big{(}\beta\ast i_{u}\Big{)}=\Big{(}% \beta^{\prime}\ast i_{u^{\prime}}\Big{)}\odot\Big{(}i_{f}\ast\varepsilon\Big{)}.$ The relevant diagrams for the previous identity are: $C$$E$$\Downarrow i_{u}$$D$$\Downarrow\beta$$B,$$\Downarrow\varepsilon$$C$$\Downarrow i_{g}$$D^{\prime}$$\scriptstyle{v^{\prime}}$$\scriptstyle{u}$$\scriptstyle{u}$$\scriptstyle{g}$$\scriptstyle{g}$$\scriptstyle{u^{\prime}}$$\scriptstyle{f}$$\scriptstyle{v}$$\scriptstyle{v}$ $D$$C$$E$$\Downarrow\varepsilon$$\Downarrow\beta^{\prime}$$\Downarrow i_{f}$$B;$$\Downarrow i_{u^{\prime}}$$D^{\prime}$$C$$\scriptstyle{u^{\prime}}$$\scriptstyle{u^{\prime}}$$\scriptstyle{u}$$\scriptstyle{v^{\prime}}$$\scriptstyle{v^{\prime}}$$\scriptstyle{f}$$\scriptstyle{f}$$\scriptstyle{v}$$\scriptstyle{g}$ (U5) if $w:A\rightarrow B$ is a morphism in $\mathbf{W}$, $v:A\rightarrow B$ is any morphism and there exists an invertible $2$-morphism $\alpha:v\Rightarrow w$, then $v$ belongs to $\mathbf{W}$.
Definition 1.3. [Po, §2.1] Let us fix any $2$ charts $(\widetilde{U},G,\pi)$ and $(\widetilde{U}^{\prime},G^{\prime},\pi^{\prime})$ for non-empty open subsets $U,U^{\prime}$ of $X$. Then a change of charts with source $(\widetilde{U},G,\pi)$ and target $(\widetilde{U}^{\prime},G^{\prime},\pi^{\prime})$ is any diffeomorphism $\lambda:\hat{U}\rightarrow\hat{U}^{\prime}$ defined between connected open sets $\hat{U}\subseteq\widetilde{U}$ and $\hat{U}^{\prime}\subseteq\widetilde{U}^{\prime}$, such that $\pi^{\prime}\circ\lambda=\pi$. In particular, for consistency of notations, we will say that also the empty map $\varnothing\rightarrow\varnothing$ is a change of charts. If $\lambda$ is any change of charts, we denote by $\operatorname{dom}f$ its domain and by $\operatorname{cod}f$ its codomain. If $x\in\operatorname{dom}f$, then $\operatorname{germ}_{x}f$ denotes the germ of $f$ at $x$. An embedding is any change of charts $\lambda$ as before, such that $\operatorname{dom}\lambda=\widetilde{U}$. Two charts as before are called compatible if for each pair $\widetilde{x}\in\widetilde{U}$, $\widetilde{x}^{\prime}\in\widetilde{U}^{\prime}$ with $\pi(\widetilde{x})=\pi^{\prime}(\widetilde{x}^{\prime})$ there exists a change of charts $\lambda$ with $\widetilde{x}\in\operatorname{dom}\lambda$ and $\widetilde{x}^{\prime}\in\operatorname{cod}\lambda$.
Definition 1.9. Let us fix any orbifold atlas $\mathcal{U}$ as before and let $P$ be any subset of $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U})$. We say that $P$ is a good subset of $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U})$ if the following property hold: (P1) for each $\lambda\in\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U})$ and for each $\widetilde{x}\in\operatorname{dom}\lambda$ there exists $\hat{\lambda}\in P$ such that $\widetilde{x}\in\operatorname{dom}\hat{\lambda}$ and $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}}\lambda=\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}}% \hat{\lambda}$. Since $P$ is a subset of $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U})$, for each $(i,i^{\prime})\in I\times I$ we write for simplicity $P(i,i^{\prime}):=P\cap\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U},i,i^{\prime})$ and $P(i,-):=\coprod_{i^{\prime}\in I}P(i,i^{\prime})$.
Definition 2.4. Given any pair $[\delta]$, $[\sigma]$ as before, we define their horizontal composition as: $[\sigma]\odot[\delta]:=[\theta]:[\hat{f}^{1}]\Longrightarrow[\hat{f}^{3}].$
Definition 4.6. [M, example 1.5] Let $R\rightrightarrows^{\hskip-7.113189pt{}^{s}}_{\hskip-7.113189pt{}_{t}}U$ be an étale Lie groupoid, let us fix any point $u\in U$ and let us define $R_{u}:=(s,t)^{-1}\{(u,u)\}$, called the isotropy subgroup of $u$. Since both $s$ and $t$ are étale, for every point $r$ in $R_{u}$ we can find a sufficiently small open neighbourhood $W_{r}$ of $r$ where both $s$ and $t$ are invertible. Then to every point $r$ in $R_{u}$ we can associate the set map: $\tilde{r}:=t\circ(s|_{W_{r}})^{-1}:\,s(W_{r})\rightarrow t(W_{r});$ this is a diffeomorphism between two open neighbourhoods of $u$ and it fixes $u$. Then we can define a set map (actually, a group homomorphism) $\chi_{u}$ from $R_{u}$ to the group of germs of smooth maps defined around $u$ and which fix $u$. Then we say that $R\rightrightarrows^{\hskip-7.113189pt{}^{s}}_{\hskip-7.113189pt{}_{t}}U$ is effective (or reduced) if $\chi_{u}$ is injective for every $u$ in $U$.
Definition 1.12. Let us fix two orbifold atlases $\mathcal{U}=\{(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ and $\mathcal{V}=\{(\widetilde{V}_{j},H_{j},\phi_{j})\}_{j\in J}$ for $X$ and $Y$ respectively and let $\hat{f}=\left(f,\overline{f},\left\{\widetilde{f}_{i}\right\}_{i\in I},P_{f},% \nu_{f}\right)\quad\textrm{and}\quad\hat{f}^{\prime}:=\left(f^{\prime},% \overline{f}^{\prime},\left\{\widetilde{f}^{\prime}_{i}\right\}_{i\in I},P_{f}% ^{\prime},\nu_{f}^{\prime}\right)$ be two representatives of orbifold maps from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{V}$. We say that $\hat{f}$ is equivalent to $\hat{f}^{\prime}$ if and only if $f=f^{\prime}$, $\overline{f}=\overline{f}^{\prime}$, $\widetilde{f}_{i}=\widetilde{f}^{\prime}_{i}$ for all $i\in I$, and $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu_{f}(\lambda)=% \operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu_{f}^{\prime}(% \lambda^{\prime})$ for all $i\in I$, for all $\lambda\in P_{f}(i,-)$, $\lambda^{\prime}\in P_{f}^{\prime}(i,-)$ and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\operatorname{dom}\lambda\cap\operatorname{dom}\lambda^{\prime}$ with $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}_{i}}\lambda=\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde% {x}_{i}}\lambda^{\prime}$. This defines an equivalence relation (it is reflexive by (Q5d)). The equivalence class of $\hat{f}$ will be denoted by $[\hat{f}]=\left(f,\overline{f},\left\{\widetilde{f}_{i}\right\}_{i\in I},\left% [P_{f},\nu_{f}\right]\right):\,\mathcal{U}\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}$ and it is called an orbifold map from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{V}$ over the continuous map $f:X\rightarrow Y$.
Definition 6.1. Let us fix any pair of reduced orbifold atlases $\mathcal{U}=\{(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$, and $\mathcal{V}$ on $X$ and $Y$ respectively and any morphism $[\hat{w}]=\left(w,\overline{w},\left\{\widetilde{w}_{i}\right\}_{i\in I},\left% [P_{w},\nu_{w}\right]\right):\,\mathcal{U}\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}.$ Then we say that $[\hat{w}]$ is a weak equivalence of orbifold atlases iff the following $2$ conditions hold: (W1) the continuous map $w:X\rightarrow Y$ is an homeomorphism; (W2) for each $i\in I$ the chart $(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},w\circ\pi_{i})$ on $Y$ is compatible with the atlas $\mathcal{V}$ (equivalently, it belongs to the maximal atlas $\mathcal{V}^{\textrm{max}}$ associated to $\mathcal{V}$). Given any two atlases $\mathcal{U}^{1},\mathcal{U}^{2}$, we say that they are weakly equivalent if and only if there is an atlas $\mathcal{U}^{\prime}$ and a pair of weak equivalences of orbifold atlases as follows: $\mathcal{U}^{1}$$\mathcal{U}^{\prime}$$\mathcal{U}^{2}.$$\scriptstyle{[\hat{w}^{1}]}$$\scriptstyle{[\hat{w}^{2}]}$ In that case we write $\mathcal{U}^{1}\sim\mathcal{U}^{2}$ (we will prove in proposition 6.7 below that actually this is an equivalence relation).
Definition 4.1. [L, definition 2.11] A Lie groupoid is the datum of two smooth manifolds $R,U$ and five smooth maps: • $s,t:R\rightrightarrows U$ such that both $s$ and $t$ are submersions (so that the fiber products of the form ${R}\,_{t}\times_{s}\,{\cdots\phantom{R}\,_{t}\times_{s}R}$ (for finitely many terms) exist); these two maps are usually called source and target of the Lie groupoid; • $m:{R}\,_{t}\times_{s}\,{R}\rightarrow R$, called multiplication; • $i:R\rightarrow R$, known as inverse of the Lie groupoid; • $e:U\rightarrow R$, called identity; which satisfy the following axioms: (S1) $s\circ e=1_{U}=t\circ e$; (S2) if we denote by $pr_{1}$ and $pr_{2}$ the two projections from the fibred product ${R}\,_{t}\times_{s}\,{R}$ to $R$, then we have $s\circ m=s\circ pr_{1}$ and $t\circ m=t\circ pr_{2}$; (S3) the two morphisms $m\circ(1_{R}\times m)$ and $m\circ(m\times 1_{R})$ from ${R}\,_{t}\times_{s}\,{R\,_{t}\times_{s}R}$ to $R$ are equal; (S4) the two morphisms $m\circ(e\circ s,1_{R})$ and $m\circ(1_{R},e\circ t)$ from $R$ to $R$ are both equal to the identity of $R$; (S5) $i\circ i=1_{R}$, $s\circ i=t$ (and therefore $t\circ i=s$); moreover, we require that $m\circ(1_{R},i)=e\circ s$ and $m\circ(i,1_{R})=e\circ t$:
Definition 1.1. [MP, §1] Let $X$ be a paracompact, second countable, Hausdorff topological space and let $U\subseteq X$ be open and non-empty. Then a reduced orbifold chart (also known as reduced uniformizing system) of dimension $n$ for $U$ is the datum of: • a connected open subset $\widetilde{U}$ of $\mathbb{R}^{n}$; • a finite group $G$ of diffeomorphisms of $\widetilde{U}$; • a continuous, surjective and $G$-invariant map $\pi:\widetilde{U}\rightarrow U$, which induces an homeomorphism between $\widetilde{U}/G$ and $U$, where we give to $\widetilde{U}/G$ the quotient topology.
Definition 4.3. [PS, definition 2.3] Let us suppose we have fixed $2$ morphisms of Lie groupoid $(\psi^{m},\Psi^{m}):\,\,(R\rightrightarrows^{\hskip-7.113189pt{}^{s}}_{\hskip-% 7.113189pt{}_{t}}U)\rightarrow(R^{\prime}\rightrightarrows^{\hskip-7.966772pt{% }^{s^{\prime}}}_{\hskip-7.966772pt{}_{t^{\prime}}}U^{\prime})$ for $m=1,2$. Then a $2$-morphism (also known as natural transformation) $\alpha:(\psi^{1},\Psi^{1})\Rightarrow(\psi^{2},\Psi^{2})$ is the datum of any smooth map $\alpha:U\rightarrow R^{\prime}$ such that the following conditions hold: (T1) $s^{\prime}\circ\alpha=\psi^{1}$ and $t^{\prime}\circ\alpha=\psi^{2}$; (T2) $m^{\prime}\circ(\alpha\circ s,\Psi^{2})=m^{\prime}\circ(\Psi^{1},\alpha\circ t).$
Definition 1.16. Let us fix any continuous function $f:X\rightarrow Y$ and let $\mathcal{U}=\{(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ and $\mathcal{V}:=\{(\widetilde{V}_{j},H_{j},\phi_{j})\}_{j\in J}$ be orbifold atlases for $X$ and $Y$ respectively. Moreover, let us fix $2$ morphisms from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{V}$ over $f$: $[\hat{f}^{m}]:=\left(f,\overline{f}^{m},\left\{\widetilde{f}^{m}_{i}\right\}_{% i\in I},\left[P_{f}^{m},\nu_{f}^{m}\right]\right),\quad\textrm{for }m=1,2.$ Then a representative of a $2$-morphism from $[\hat{f}^{1}]$ to $[\hat{f}^{2}]$ is any set of data: $\delta:=\left\{\left(\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a},\delta_{i}^{a}\right)\right\}_{i\in I% ,a\in A(i)}$ such that: (R1) for all $i\in I$ the set $\{\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}\}_{a\in A(i)}$ is an open covering of $\widetilde{U}_{i}$ (we allow the possibility that some of the $\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}$’s are empty sets); (R2) for all $i\in I$ and for all $a\in A(i)$, $\delta_{i}^{a}$ is a change of charts in $\mathcal{V}$ with $\widetilde{f}^{1}_{i}\left(\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}\right)\subseteq\operatorname{% dom}\delta_{i}^{a}\subseteq\widetilde{V}_{\overline{f}^{1}(i)},\quad\widetilde% {f}^{2}_{i}\left(\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}\right)\subseteq\operatorname{cod}\delta% _{i}^{a}\subseteq\widetilde{V}_{\overline{f}^{2}(i)};$ (R3) for all $i\in I$, for all $a\in A(i)$ and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}$ we have $\widetilde{f}_{i}^{2}(\widetilde{x}_{i})=\delta_{i}^{a}\circ\widetilde{f}_{i}^% {1}(\widetilde{x}_{i});$ (R4) for all $i\in I$, for all $a,a^{\prime}\in A(i)$ and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}\cap\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a^{\prime}}$ (if non empty) we have $\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\delta_{i}^{a}=% \operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\delta_{i}^{a^{% \prime}}$ (note that (R3) only proves that $\delta_{i}^{a}$ coincides with $\delta_{i}^{a^{\prime}}$ on the set $\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}(\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}\cap\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a^{\prime}})$, that in general is not an open set since $\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}$ can be non-open); (R5) for all $(i,i^{\prime})\in I\times I$, for all $(a,a^{\prime})\in A(i)\times A(i^{\prime})$, for all $\lambda\in\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U},i,i^{\prime})$, and for all $\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\operatorname{dom}\lambda\cap\widetilde{U}_{i}^{a}$ such that $\lambda(\widetilde{x}_{i})\in\widetilde{U}_{i^{\prime}}^{a^{\prime}}$ there exist $\left(P_{f}^{m},\nu_{f}^{m}\right)\in\left[P_{f}^{m},\nu_{f}^{m}\right],\quad% \lambda^{m}\in P_{f}^{m}(i,i^{\prime})\quad\textrm{for }m=1,2$ such that $\displaystyle\widetilde{x}_{i}\in\operatorname{dom}\lambda^{m},\quad% \operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{x}_{i}}\lambda^{m}=\operatorname{germ}_{% \widetilde{x}_{i}}\lambda\quad\textrm{for }m=1,2,$ $\displaystyle\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}^{2}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu% _{f}^{2}(\lambda^{2})\cdot\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}(% \widetilde{x}_{i})}\delta_{i}^{a}=\operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i^{% \prime}}^{1}(\lambda(\widetilde{x}_{i}))}\delta_{i^{\prime}}^{a^{\prime}}\cdot% \operatorname{germ}_{\widetilde{f}_{i}^{1}(\widetilde{x}_{i})}\nu_{f}^{1}(% \lambda^{1}).$
Definition 1.8. [CR, §4.1] Let $f:X\rightarrow Y$ be any continuous map between topological spaces and let $U\subseteq X$ and $V\subseteq Y$ be open subsets such that $f(U)\subseteq V$. Let us suppose that there exists charts $(\widetilde{U},G,\pi)$ for $U$ and $(\widetilde{V},H,\phi)$ for $V$. Then a local lift of $f$ with respect to these 2 charts is any smooth map $\widetilde{f}:\widetilde{U}\rightarrow\widetilde{V}$ such that $\phi\circ\widetilde{f}=f\circ\pi$.
Definition 1.5. [MP, §1] Let $X$ be a paracompact, second countable, Hausdorff topological space; a reduced orbifold atlas of dimension $n$ on $X$ is any family $\mathcal{U}=\{(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ of reduced orbifolds charts of dimension $n$, such that: (i) the family $\{\pi_{i}(\widetilde{U}_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ is an open cover of $X$; (ii) for every pair $(i,i^{\prime})\in I\times I$ and for every $x\in\pi_{i}(\widetilde{U}_{i})\cap\pi_{i^{\prime}}(\widetilde{U}_{i^{\prime}})$ there exists a chart $(\widetilde{U},G,\pi)$ such that $x\in\pi(\widetilde{U})\subseteq\pi_{i}(\widetilde{U}_{i})\cap\pi_{i^{\prime}}(% \widetilde{U}_{i^{\prime}})$ and there exists a pair of embeddings of $(\widetilde{U},G,\pi)$ in $(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})$ and $(\widetilde{U}_{i^{\prime}},G_{i^{\prime}},\pi_{i^{\prime}})$ respectively. Given any orbifold atlas $\mathcal{U}$ as before and any pair $(i,i^{\prime})\in I\times I$, we denote by $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U},i,i^{\prime})$ the set of all changes of charts $\lambda$ from $(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})$ to $(\widetilde{U}_{i^{\prime}},G_{i^{\prime}},\pi_{i^{\prime}})$ and we set $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U}):=\coprod_{(i,i^{\prime})\in I\times I}\mathcal{C}h(% \mathcal{U},i,i^{\prime})$.
Definition 3.1. Given any reduced orbifold atlas $\mathcal{U}=\{(\widetilde{U}_{i},G_{i},\pi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ on a space $X$, we define the identity of $\mathcal{U}$ as the morphism $\textrm{id}_{\mathcal{U}}:=\left(\textrm{id}_{X},\textrm{id}_{I},\left\{% \textrm{id}_{\widetilde{U}_{i}}\right\}_{i\in I},\left[\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U% }),\nu_{\textrm{id}}\right]\right):\mathcal{U}\longrightarrow\mathcal{U}$ where $\nu_{\textrm{id}}$ is the identity on $\mathcal{C}h(\mathcal{U})$. Given any pair of reduced orbifold atlases $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ and any morphism $[\hat{f}]=(f,\overline{f},\{\widetilde{f}_{i}\}_{i\in I},[P_{f},\nu_{f}])$ from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{V}$, we define the $2$-identity $i_{[\hat{f}]}$ as the class of $\left\{\left(\widetilde{U}_{i},\textrm{id}_{\widetilde{V}_{\overline{f}(i)}}% \right)\right\}_{i\in I}.$ Moreover, for each orbifold atlas $\mathcal{U}$ on a topological space $X$, we set $i_{\mathcal{U}}:=i_{\textrm{id}_{\mathcal{U}}}$.
Definition 4.2. A diagram $D\colon P\to\mathcal{K}$ is smooth if, for every limit $x\in P$, the diagram $(D(yx)\colon Dy\to Dx)_{y<x}$ is a colimit cocone on the restriction of $D$ to $\downdownarrows x$. A good diagram $D\colon P\to\mathcal{K}$ is a smooth diagram whose shape category $P$ is a good poset.
Definition 4.1. We say that a poset $P$ is good if it is well-founded and has a least element $\perp$. A good poset is called $\kappa$-good if all its initial segments $\downarrow x$ have cardinality $<\kappa$.
Definition 2.2. Given a Pultr template $\mathcal{T}=(P,Q,\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2})$ the central Pultr functor $\Gamma_{\mathcal{T}}$ is the following construction: For a digraph $H$, the vertices of $\Gamma_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ are the homomorphisms $g:P\rightarrow H$, and the arcs of $\Gamma_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ are the couples $(g_{1},g_{2})$ such that there exists a homomorphism $h:Q\rightarrow H$ with $g_{1}=h\circ\epsilon_{1}$, $g_{2}=h\circ\epsilon_{2}$.
Definition 2.3. Given a Pultr template, $\mathcal{T}=(P,Q,\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2})$ the left Pultr functor $\Lambda_{\mathcal{T}}$ is the following construction: For a digraph $G$, $\Lambda_{\mathcal{T}}(G)$ contains one copy $P_{u}$ of $P$ for every vertex $u$ of $G$, and for every arc $(u,v)$ of $G$, $\Lambda_{\mathcal{T}}(G)$ contains a copy $Q_{u,v}$ of $Q$ with $\epsilon_{1}[P]$ identified with $P_{u}$ and $\epsilon_{2}[P]$ identified with $P_{v}$.
Definition 3.1. For a digraph $H$, the vertices of $\delta_{R}(H)$ are all the pairs $(R^{-},R^{+})\subseteq V(H)^{2}$ such that $R^{-}\Rrightarrow R^{+}$. (Note that $(\emptyset,V(H))$ and $(V(H),\emptyset)$ are vertices of $\delta_{R}(H)$.) $(R^{-},R^{+})\to(S^{-},S^{+})$ is an arc of $\delta_{R}(H)$ if and only if $R^{+}\cap S^{-}\neq\emptyset$.
Definition 4.5. Suppose that $Q$ is an oriented path with $m$ arcs and vertex set $\{0,1,\dotsc,m\}$. Let $\mathcal{T}=(\vec{P}_{0},Q,\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2})$, where $\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2}$ map the one-vertex graph $\vec{P}_{0}$ to the end-points of $Q$. For a digraph $H$, let the vertex set of $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ be $V=\{(x,X_{1},\dotsc,X_{m})\colon x\in V(H),\ X_{i}\subseteq V(H)\text{ for each $i$, $X_{m}\Rrightarrow x$}\}$. There is an arc in $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ from $(x,X_{1},\dotsc,X_{m})$ to $(y,Y_{1},\dotsc,Y_{m})$ if (1a) $x\in Y_{1}$ if $0\to 1$ in $Q$, (1b) $y\in X_{1}$ if $1\to 0$ in $Q$; and (2) for each $i=1,\dotsc,m-1$: (a) $X_{i}\subseteq Y_{i+1}$ if $i\to i+1$ in $Q$, (b) $Y_{i}\subseteq X_{i+1}$ if $i+1\to i$ in $Q$.
Definition 2.1. A Pultr template is a quadruple $\mathcal{T}=(P,Q,\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2})$ where $P$, $Q$ are digraphs and $\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2}$ homomorphisms of $P$ to $Q$.
Definition 6.1. Let $P=\vec{P}_{1}=\bigl{(}\{0,1\},\{(0,1)\}\bigr{)}$; let $Q$ have vertex set $\{0,1,\dotsc,10\}$ and arcs $0\to 1\to 2\to 3\to 4$, $6\to 7\to 8\to 9\to 10$, $7\to 5\to 3$. Let $\epsilon_{1}:P\to Q$, $\epsilon_{1}(0)=0$, $\epsilon_{1}(1)=1$, and $\epsilon_{2}:P\to Q$, $\epsilon_{2}(0)=9$, $\epsilon_{2}(1)=10$. Consider the Pultr template $\mathcal{T}=(P,Q,\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2})$, see figure. For a digraph $H$, define $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ by: $\displaystyle V(\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H))=\Bigl{\{}(S^{-},S^{+},S^{--},S^{++},S% ^{---},S^{+++},S^{-*+++},S^{--*+++})\in(2^{V(H)})^{8}\colon\\ \displaystyle\qquad\qquad\text{if }S^{+}\neq\emptyset\text{, then }S^{---}% \Rrightarrow S^{--*+++}\Bigr{\}}$ and $S\to T$ in $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ if • $S^{+}\cap T^{-}\neq\emptyset$, • $S^{-}\subseteq T^{--}$, • $S^{--}\subseteq T^{---}$, • $T^{+}\subseteq S^{++}$, • $T^{++}\subseteq S^{+++}$, • $S^{-*+++}\subseteq T^{--*+++}$, and • $S^{-}=\emptyset$ or $S^{+++}\subseteq T^{-*+++}$.
Definition 4.1. For a digraph $H$, the vertices of $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ are all the pairs $(a,A)$ such that $a\in V(H)$ and $A\subseteq V(H)$. (Note that each $(a,\emptyset)$ with $a\in V(H)$ is a vertex of $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$.) $(a,A)\to(b,B)$ is an arc of $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}(H)$ if and only if $b\in A\Rrightarrow B$.
Definition 8.1. Let $\mathcal{F}$ be a set of digraphs and $H$ a digraph. We say that $\mathcal{F}$ is a complete set of obstructions for $H$ or that $(\mathcal{F},H)$ is a homomorphism duality if for any digraph $G$, $G\to H\quad\Leftrightarrow\quad\forall\,F\in\mathcal{F}\colon F\nrightarrow G.$ We also say that $H$ has tree duality if it admits a complete set of obstructions all of whose elements are trees, and $H$ has finite duality if it admits a finite complete set of obstructions.
Definition 4.3. For a digraph $H$, the vertices of $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{\prime}(H)$ are all the triples $(a,A_{1},A_{2})$ such that $a\in V(H)$, $A_{1},A_{2}\subseteq V(H)$ and $A_{1}\Rrightarrow A_{2}$. $(a,A_{1},A_{2})\to(b,B_{1},B_{2})$ is an arc of $\Omega_{\mathcal{T}}^{\prime}(H)$ if and only if $b\in A_{1}$ and $B_{1}\subseteq A_{2}$.
Definition 1.1.1. 1. We will say that $D\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ is weakly negative if $\{0\}\in D$ and $D\perp(\cup_{i>1}D[i])$. 2. For any $i,j\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ and a weakly negative $D$ we will denote by $D_{[i,j]}$ the extension-closure of $\cup_{i\leq l\leq j}D[j]$ if $j\geq i$, and set $D_{[i,j]}=\{0\}$ if $j<i$. We denote $\cup_{i\leq j}D_{[i,j]}$ by $D_{\leq j}$; $D_{\geq i}=\cup_{j\geq i}D_{[i,j]}$.
Definition 3.3.1. We say that a weight structure $w$ for $\underline{C}$ is (left) adjacent to a $t$-structure $t$ for it if $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}=\underline{C}^{t\leq 0}$.
Definition 3.1.1. I A pair of subclasses $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0},\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\subset\operatorname{Obj}% \underline{C}$ will be said to define a weight structure $w$ for a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ if they satisfy the following conditions: (i) $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0},\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ are Karoubi-closed in $\underline{C}$ (i.e. contain all $\underline{C}$-retracts of their objects). (ii) Semi-invariance with respect to translations. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\subset\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[1]$, $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]\subset\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. (iii) Orthogonality. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\perp\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$. (iv) Weight decompositions. For any $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists a distinguished triangle $X\to M\to Y{\to}X[1]$ such that $X\in\underline{C}_{w\leq 0},\ Y\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$. II The category ${\underline{Hw}}\subset\underline{C}$ whose objects are $\underline{C}_{w=0}=\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$, ${\underline{Hw}}(Z,T)=\underline{C}(Z,T)$ for $Z,T\in\underline{C}_{w=0}$, will be called the heart of $w$. III $\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq i}$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=i}$) will denote $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[i]$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[i]$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=0}[i]$). IV We denote $\underline{C}_{w\geq i}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq j}$ by $\underline{C}_{[i,j]}$ (so it equals $\{0\}$ for $i>j$). V We will say that $(\underline{C},w)$ is bounded if $\cup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\leq i}=\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}% =\cup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$. VI Let $\underline{C}$ and $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ will be triangulated categories endowed with weight structures $w$ and $w^{\prime}$, respectively; let $F:\underline{C}\to\underline{C}^{\prime}$ be an exact functor. $F$ will be called left weight-exact (with respect to $w,w^{\prime}$) if it maps $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ into $\underline{C}^{\prime}_{w^{\prime}\leq 0}$; it will be called right weight-exact if it maps $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ into $\underline{C}^{\prime}_{w^{\prime}\geq 0}$. $F$ is called weight-exact if it is both left and right weight-exact. VII Let $H$ be a full subcategory of a triangulated $\underline{C}$. We will say that $H$ is negative if $\operatorname{Obj}H\perp(\cup_{i>0}\operatorname{Obj}(H[i]))$. VIII The small envelope of an additive category $A$ is the category $A^{\prime}\subset\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(A)$ whose objects are $(X,p)$ for $X\in\operatorname{Obj}A$ and $p\in A(X,X)$ such that $p^{2}=p$ and there exist $Y\in\operatorname{Obj}A$ and $q\in A(X,Y)$, $s\in A(Y,X)$ satisfying $sq=1-p$, $qs=\operatorname{id}_{Y}$. Certainly, $A^{\prime}$-morphism groups are given by the standard formula for $\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(A)$: $A^{\prime}((X,p),(X^{\prime},p^{\prime}))=\{f\in A(X,X^{\prime}):\ p^{\prime}f% =fp=f\}.$
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a compactly generated stable presentable $\infty$-category. Then, $\mathscr{C}$ satisfies the telescope hypothesis (TH) if the kernel of every smashing localization $j:\mathscr{C}\rightarrow\mathscr{D}$ is generated by compact objects of $\mathscr{C}$. Now, suppose that $\mathscr{M}$ is a compactly generated symmetric monoidal stable presentable $\infty$-category and that $\mathscr{C}$ is a compactly generated $\mathscr{M}$-linear category. Say that $\mathscr{C}$ satisfies the $\mathscr{M}$-linear telescope hypothesis (LTH) if the kernel of every $\mathscr{M}$-linear smashing localization $j:\mathscr{C}\rightarrow\mathscr{D}$ is generated by compact objects of $\mathscr{C}$. Finally, suppose that $X$ is an étale sheaf over $R$, and let $\alpha:X\rightarrow\mathscr{C}\mathrm{at}^{\mathrm{desc}}$ classify a stack $\mathscr{M}\mathrm{od}^{\alpha}$ of linear categories. Say that $\mathscr{M}\mathrm{od}^{\alpha}$ satisfies the stacky telescope hypothesis (STH) if for every smashing localization of stacks $\mathscr{M}\mathrm{od}^{\alpha}\rightarrow\mathscr{M}\mathrm{od}^{\beta}$ and every map $\operatorname{Spec}S\rightarrow X$, the kernel of $\mathrm{Mod}_{S}^{\alpha}\rightarrow\mathrm{Mod}_{S}^{\beta}$ is generated by compact objects of $\mathrm{Mod}_{S}^{\alpha}$.
Definition 2.4. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a category. We say that ${\mathcal{C}}$ is semi-monoidal when it satisfies all the properties for a monoidal category except for the requirement of a unit object — i.e. there exists a tensor $(\ \Box\ ):{\mathcal{C}}\times{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{C}}$ together with a natural object-indexed family of associativity isomorphisms $\{\tau_{A,B,C}:A\Box(B\Box C)\rightarrow(A\Box B)\Box C\}_{A,B,C\in Ob({% \mathcal{C}})}$ satisfying MacLane’s pentagon condition $(\tau_{A,B,C}\Box 1_{D})\tau_{A,B\Box C,D}(1_{A}\Box\tau_{B,C,D})\ =\ \tau_{A% \Box B,C,D}\tau_{A,B,C\Box D}$ When there also exists a natural object-indexed natural family of symmetry isomorphisms $\{\sigma_{X,Y}:X\Box Y\rightarrow Y\Box X\}_{X,Y\in Ob({\mathcal{C}})}$ satisfying MacLane’s hexagon condition $\tau_{A,B,C}\sigma_{A\Box B,C}\tau_{A,B,C}\ =\ (\sigma_{A,C}\Box 1_{B})\tau_{A% ,C,B}(1_{A}\Box\sigma_{B,C})$ we say that $({\mathcal{C}},\Box,\tau,\sigma)$ is a symmetric semi-monoidal category. A functor $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ between two semi-monoidal categories $({\mathcal{C}},\Box_{\mathcal{C}})$ and $(\mathcal{D},\Box_{\mathcal{D}})$ is called (strictly) semi-monoidal when $\Gamma(f\Box_{\mathcal{C}}g)=\Gamma(f)\Box_{\mathcal{D}}\Gamma(g)$. All monoidal categories are semi-monoidal, but not vice versa; the relationship is precisely analogous to that between monoids and semigroups. When a semi-monoidal category does not contain a unit object, we call it unitless monoidal. When a semi-monoidal category has only one object, we call it untyped monoidal, or simply untyped.
